article.description:
Jeff Foster provided a huge lift of the
bench with nine points and 10 rebounds in the Pacers' 80-66 victory over the Grlzzlies.
article.headline: Foster lifts Pacers from bench in win over Grizz
article.linkText: Foster lifts Pacers from bench in win over Grizz
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Jeff Foster is slowly but surely working his way back into the Indiana rotation. The center, playing his fifth game of the season after a long rehabilitation from a heel injury, provided a huge lift of the bench with nine points and 10 rebounds in the Pacers' 80-66 victory over the Memphis Grizzlies on Saturday night. "I've been playing basketball for a week and a day," Foster said. "I have some good days and some bad days. Today was a good day. "I'm just looking to get in a rhythm and get my legs back." Jermaine O'Neal had 20 points and 14 rebounds and Stephen Jackson added 16 points, all but two of them in the second half. Jackson, coming off a season-high 30 points against Washington on Thursday night, played fewer than 10 minutes and had three fouls in the first half, when the Pacers took an early lead but didn't take control for good until Foster entered the game and gave Indiana an immediate boost. "Jeff gave us great energy," Pacers coach Rick Carlisle said. "He's getting better every game. We're still keeping him around 20 minutes, but we'd like to pick that up a little more." Foster played just under 20 minutes, hit 3-of-4 shots from the field and 3-of-4 free throws. He also had two steals and no turnovers. A 3-pointer by Anthony Johnson and a layup by Foster put the Pacers up 10, then after the first of three 3-pointers by the Grizzlies' Shane Battier, the Pacers closed the period with two free throws by Foster, a dunk by rookie Danny Granger off an assist by Foster and a rebound tip by Foster for a 24-9 lead. "Just having Jeff back helps us out so much," Jackson said. "Jeff's one of those players in the league who plays his role to a T. He's not going to score 30 points but he makes everybody better." Memphis, which shot 34 percent for the game, cut the lead to eight on consecutive 3-pointers by Battier and Mike Miller midway through the second quarter, but all seven Memphis points the rest of the period came on free throws. Indiana's biggest lead of the period was 39-22. Pau Gasol, who was 1-of-7 from the field in the first half and 2-for-12 for the game, hit four straight free throws, but Indiana outscored the Grizzlies 4-1 from the foul line in the final minute and took a 43-27 lead at halftime. Memphis twice came within nine, but Jackson and Johnson hit 3-pointers during a 10-0 run that broke the game open. The Grizzlies closed to 63-52 early in the final period, but the Pacers pulled away again on a basket and free throw by Jackson and two straight baskets by O'Neal. "They jumped on us. We just could not hit anything to save our lives," said Battier, who led Memphis with 13 points. "It was just an uphill battle for us to climb after the first couple of minutes, and it proved to be too much." Memphis coach Mike Fratello said the Grizzlies -- second in the league in scoring defense -- were too lax. "Our normal defense wasn't there. They took advantage of their opportunities tonight," Fratello said. Gasol added 11 points for the Grizzlies. "Most of my shots were falling short," he said. "I'm starting to second-guess myself. ... I am not playing with much confidence."

Game notes
The Grizzlies' nine points in the first quarter and 27 in the first half were season lows for them and for any Indiana opponent. ... Austin Croshere started for the Pacers after missing the first half of Thursday's game, when he was stuck in a snowstorm and couldn't get to the arena in time. He had seven points and 11 rebounds but left with a lower back strain in the second half. ... Indiana has won 10 straight games at home against the Grizzlies. ... Memphis, one of the worst foul-shooting teams in the league, made 11-of-20 against the Pacers. ... Indiana's Ron Artest didn't play for the second straight game because of a sore wrist.
